Path::contents/Session.htm::Author: Ben Ambrose
Path::contents/Session.htm::Title: Session
Path::contents/Session.htm::InnerText:
Session
  Once connection with the SwimClubMeet database, the drop-down combobox will be populated with your clubs sessions.
  Not all sessions will be visible if the option to hide closed sessions is enabled.
  When youselect a session from the list,  events and heats  are loaded for that session.
Path::contents/About.htm::Author: Ben Ambrose
Path::contents/About.htm::Title: About
Path::contents/About.htm::Description: Introduction and broad description of the Marshall application for SwimClubMeet.
Path::contents/About.htm::InnerText:
About
  Marshall is a stand alone application for SwimClubMeet.
  Use it to rally your swimmers for events. 
  Change the entrant's qualification status. Disqualify or scratch swimmers.
  Quick entry of club members into empty lanes - should you have (very) late arrivals.
   
  Use Marshall in colaboration with Timekeeper to create a 'paperless' swimming session.
   
  Written in Embarcadero RAD Studio (Pascal) using FMX it's ready for Multi-Platform delivery. Currently only compiled for Windows 64bit. It's form factor is designed for Microsofts TouchPad Pro.
Path::contents/Login.htm::Author: Ben Ambrose
Path::contents/Login.htm::Title: Login
Path::contents/Login.htm::Description: Login to the MS SQLEXPRESS server.
Path::contents/Login.htm::InnerText:
Login
  To login into the MS SQLEXPRESS database server, you need a IP address or NAME PATH, user name and password. Else, set up correctly, you can use the operation services authentication.
  Once connection has been established, the Connect button is replaced by the Disconnect button.
  Being connect results in listboxes and other data aware controls to be populated with SwimClubMeet data.
  Clicking the disconnect button will log you out of the server and end the connection. Closing the application will also perform the same task.
